\title{Uncertainty in a dynamic game of R\&D with positive externalities}
\author{Lu Hao}
\date{April 2020}

\begin{document}

\maketitle
\section{Abstract} 

This dissertation extends the model of d'Aspremont and Jacquemin (1988) by introducing uncertainty in the spillover parameter. I consider how different types of monitoring affect R\&D efforts under R\&D cooperation and R\&D competition. I find that under perfect monitoring, R\&D in the latter is higher for symmetric distributions of $\beta$. Interestingly, R\&D under imperfect monitoring is higher than that under perfect monitoring. I also examine the sustainability of the R\&D cooperation strategy in an infinitely repeated game. For a sufficiently large discount rate, full R\&D cooperation is sustainable under perfect monitoring while partial R\&D cooperation is possible under imperfect private monitoring. 

\section{Introduction}

Industrial organisation literature on R\&D investment is rich because of its broad implications in topics ranging from economic growth (Dasgupta (1980), Schumpeter (1947)) to competition policy (Jacquemin, 2000). While the direct consequence of successful R\&D can be easily represented by reduced unit costs of the firm investing in R\&D, modelling strategic R\&D and its indirect effects have led to many insightful and sometimes counter-intuitive results. In particular, investigations of a two-stage game in which firms first commit to R\&D activities (which decreases unit production costs) and then compete in the product market have generated much interest. 

Brander and Spencer (1983) compare R\&D levels between a strategic R\&D duopoly model and a non-strategic model. In the former, firms play a two-stage game, simultaneously choosing R\&D levels in the first stage and (homogenous) output quantities in the second stage. It is assumed that the second stage play follows a Cournot equilibrium and firms can anticipate its outcome when deciding first stage R\&D level. In the latter model, R\&D investment and output are simultaneously decided so that there are no strategic reasons behind R\&D investment. The comparison showed that strategic R\&D considerations induce each firm to use more R\&D than required to minimise the cost of output it produces.  

D’Aspermont and Jacquemin (1988) extend Brander and Spencer’s two-stage strategic R\&D model by introducing spillover effects so that one firm’s R\&D investment also lowers the unit cost of the other firm by an amount proportionate to a spillover parameter. While maintaining that firms play the Cournot equilibrium in the second stage, they consider both R\&D cartelisation and R\&D competition in the first stage. In R\&D cartelisation, firms set R\&D levels to maximise total profit. In R\&D competition, firms set R\&D levels to maximise own profit, so that R\&D competition leads to a subgame perfect Nash equilibrium. They show that when spillover is large, R\&D cartelisation results in higher R\&D levels than R\&D competition. The opposite is true for small spillovers. Spence (1984) and Katz (1986) reached similar conclusions with slightly different formulations of the same problem. 

Kamien et al (1992) build on D’Aspermont and Jacquemin’s model by adding two additional cases – R\&D joint venture (RJV) cartelisation and RJV competition.\footnote{They also use a more general R\&D production function and extend the analysis to more than two firms.} Under a RJV, firms avoid duplication of R\&D activities and maximise the spillover effects. As with D’Aspermont and Jacquemin’s paper, cartelisation implies that firms maximise joint profits while competition implies that firms maximise individual profits. Among the four cases examined – R\&D Competition, R\&D Cartelisation, RJV Competition and RJV Cartelisation, it was shown that RJV cartelisation is most effective in unit cost reduction while RJV competition is least effective. 

The three studies provide a clear overview of simple R\&D models – the first considers R\&D as a strategic commitment device, the second introduces spillovers and the last examines special cases of the spillover parameter.\footnote{For subtle differences between the Kamien et al model and the d'Aspermont and Jacquemin model, see Amir (2000).} However, implicit in these studies is the assumption that R\&D is a multidimensional heuristic rather than a one-dimensional algorithmic process, meaning that firms pursue different areas of research and only some succeeds. This allows us to have the symmetric spillover structure in these studies. If the R\&D process was one-dimensional, then spillover can only flow from the R\&D leader to the follower.\footnote{See Tesoriere (2006) for a model of one-way spillovers.} In this light, one way to interpret the spillover parameter is as a gauge of the degree of duplication in R\&D efforts assuming that R\&D results flow between firms.\footnote{Mansfield et al. (1981) has shown that about 60 percent of the patented innovations in their sample were imitated within 4 years.} A high spillover parameter is then indicative of low duplication while a low spillover parameter implies that firms have largely overlapping research results. The Kamien et al study adopts this interpretation in their RJV models, effectively setting the spillover parameter to one because there is no R\&D duplication in a joint venture. Under this interpretation, however, it is more natural to think of the spillover parameter as a random variable rather than a deterministic constant. When firms embark on independent R\&D projects, there is uncertainty in the degree to which their results might overlap. While firms may obtain distinct R\&D results, the simultaneous invention of NMR spectroscopy by Stanford and Harvard and the independent development of CAPM by three economists are proof that independent research efforts can also lead to the same result purely by chance. 

The objective of this study is to examine the effect of uncertainty in the spillover parameter on firms’ R\&D decisions in the D’Aspermont and Jacquemin duopoly model. While their work has spawned many extensions\footnote{Henriques (1990), Kamien et al. (1992), Choi (1993), Ziss (1994), Steurs (1995), Leahy and Neary (1997), Martin (1999), Amir and Wooders (1999, 2000), Amir (2000) and Kamien and Zang (2000)}, few have introduced uncertainty into the model. Studies that do introduce uncertainty examine mainly uncertainty in the success of own R\&D efforts and not in its spillovers. (Marjit, 1991; Tishler, 2008) In this study, I focus on uncertainty in the spillover parameter to understand how R\&D level changes with different strategies when R\&D outcomes may overlap with some probability. We find that when the spillover parameter has any symmetric distribution around $\frac{1}{2}$, R\&D expenditure under R\&D cooperation is higher than that under R\&D competition. 

In section 3, I discuss the results of the d’Aspermont and Jacquemin paper and their implications. In section 4, uncertainty in the spillover parameter is introduced. Section 5 considers an infinitely repeated version of the R\&D game and section 6 concludes with the policy implications of our findings. 

\newpage
\section{Basic Model}

In the D'Aspremont and Jacquemin's (1988) duopoly model, the inverse demand function is given by $P = a-bQ$, with $a,b > 0$, $Q = q_i + q_j$  and cost function for each firm is $C_i(q_i, x_i, x_j) = (\alpha - x_i - \beta x_j)q_i + \gamma \frac{x_i^2}{2}$. The first term in the cost function captures the fact that $i$'s unit cost is decreasing in both firms' R\&D expenditure, although the decrease attributable to firm $j$'s R\&D is subjected to a multiplicative spillover parameter $\beta$. The second term captures a quadratic cost to R\&D investment.\footnote{Here, the product cost reduction ($x$) is the choice variable and the corresponding R\&D expenditure is quadratic. This is identical to models of Amir and Wooders where R\&D expenditure is the choice variable and R\&D production function ( = cost reduction) is a increasing and concave function of expenditure. Since the mapping is monotonic, we refer to cost reduction as R\&D expenditure in this paper.} Note that both firms face the identical demand and cost functions, making this a symmetric problem. The game consist of two stages: First, both firms decide simultaneously R\&D expenditure ($x_i , x_j$). Then, having observed the R\&D expenditure, both firms decide simultaneously the amount of output ($q_i, q_j$). This allows R\&D expenditure to be used as a commitment device, thus introducing strategic considerations. We restrict our attention to cases where both firms engage in Cournot competition in the second stage. By backward induction, this implies that individual profit can be expressed as\footnote{See D'Aspermont and Jacquemin (1988) for derivation.}
\begin{equation}
\label{ownProfits}
   \pi_i = \frac{1}{9b}[a-\alpha+(2-\beta)x_i+(2\beta-1)x_j]^2 - \gamma\frac{x_i^2}{2}
\end{equation}
and joint profit as 
\begin{equation}
\label{jointProfits}
    \Pi = \pi_i + \pi_j = \frac{1}{9b} \sum_{i=1}^2\left\{[(a-\alpha) + (2-\beta)x_i + (2\beta -1)x_j]^2-\gamma\frac{x_i^2}{2}\right\}
\end{equation}

We impose four reasonable constraints in this model.

\begin{assumption}
\label{basicAssumption}
\begin{align}
0 < &\alpha < a\\
0 < &\beta < 1\\
\label{cornerSolution}
x_i + \beta &x_j \leq \alpha\\
0 \leq &Q \leq \frac{a}{b}
\end{align}
\end{assumption}

The first condition ensures that the highest possible unit cost is lower than the highest possible price. The constraint on $\beta$ guarantees that firm $i$'s R\&D investment has a bigger impact on firm $i$ than firm $j$. The third condition ensures positive unit costs and the last condition ensures that price is positive.  

We consider only Cournot competition in the second stage because collusion in the second stage has a clear negative impact on welfare and is barred by most competition authorities. However, R\&D competition in the first stage, assuming firms play the Cournot equilibrium in the second stage, do not dominate R\&D cooperation in terms of social welfare. We define the R\&D cooperation and R\&D competition, as follows:

\begin{definition}
\label{cooperative and competitive play}
In \textbf{R\&D cooperation}, firms decide R\&D expenditure in the first stage to maximise joint profits in equation \ref{jointProfits}. In \textbf{R\&D competition}, firms decide R\&D expenditure in the first stage to maximise own profits in equation \ref{ownProfits}. In both strategies, we assume that Cournot equilibrium is played in stage two. 
\end{definition}

Therefore, under R\&D competition, the strategy profile is a subgame perfect Nash equilibrium. This cannot be said of R\&D cooperation since they are not playing mutual best responses in the first stage. To ensure that solution is interior and unique, we need to impose unimodality conditions on the profit functions in equation \ref{ownProfits} and \ref{jointProfits}. The following assumption guarantees that the profits functions are strictly concave.

\begin{assumption}
\begin{equation*}
\label{concavityAssumption}
b\gamma > \frac{16}{9}
\end{equation*}
\end{assumption}

The condition for concavity of equation \ref{ownProfits} is 
$9b\gamma > 2(2-\beta)^2$ and the condition for concavity in equation \ref{jointProfits} is $9b\gamma > 2(1+\beta)^2$. $b\gamma > \frac{8}{9}$ guarantees that both conditions hold for all values of $\beta$. However, assumption \ref{concavityAssumption} is stronger than $b\gamma > \frac{8}{9}$ in order to ensure the concavity of the social welfare function (defined later) as well. The assumption is satisfied when we have high cost of R\&D ($\gamma$) or high elasticity of demand (b). This is similar to the assumption in Kamien et al (1992) that R\&D is not too productive. This allows us to eliminate the corner solution where equation \ref{cornerSolution} holds with equality. We can now restate the main conclusion of D'Aspremont and Jacquemin (1998) paper in the following proposition.

\begin{proposition}
\label{ajProposition}
Under assumptions \ref{basicAssumption} and \ref{concavityAssumption}, individual R\&D expenditure is higher under R\&D cooperation, $\hat{x}$, than under R\&D competition, $x^*$, for large spillovers, $\beta > \frac{1}{2}$.\footnote{This proposition overlooks stability considerations. For a discussion on this, see Henriques (1990).}
\begin{align}
\label{xequations}
\hat{x} = \frac{(a-\alpha)(1+\beta)}{4.5b\gamma-(1+\beta)^2} &> \frac{(a-\alpha)(2-\beta)}{4.5b\gamma-(2-\beta)(1+\beta)} = x^*
\end{align}
The opposite is true for small spillovers, $\beta < \frac{1}{2}$. 
\end{proposition}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \captionsetup{width=.66\linewidth}
    \label{fig:my_label}
    \begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    axis lines = left,
    xlabel = $\beta$,
    ylabel = $x$,
]
%Below the x^* is defined
\addplot [
    domain=0:1, 
    samples=100, 
    color=red,
]
{2*(2-x)/(9-(2-x)*(1+x))};
\addlegendentry{$x^*$}
%Here the \hat{x} is defined
\addplot [
    domain=0:1, 
    samples=100, 
    color=blue,
    ]
    {2*(1+x)/(9-(1+x)*(1+x))};
\addlegendentry{$\hat{x}$}

\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{R\&D investment as a function of the spillover parameter. $a = 10, b = 1, \alpha = 8, \gamma = 2.$}
\end{figure}
This is because there are two effects to R\&D investment. The direct effect increases a firm's own profits by lowering its unit costs while the indirect effect decreases its profits by lowering the competitor's unit cost. Therefore, under R\&D competition when firms maximise own profits, equilibrium R\&D investment decreases with the spillover parameter, $\beta$. However, when firms maximise joint profits, they internalise the indirect effect of the spillover. Therefore, equilibrium R\&D expenditure under R\&D cooperation increases with the spillover parameter.\footnote{Another way to explain the difference between the two strategies is to understand the public good nature of the R\&D in this model. Under R\&D competition, firms have an incentive to free-ride on R\&D results of the other firms thus $x^*$ decreases with $\beta$. The externality is internalised with R\&D cooperation so $\hat{x}$ increases with $\beta$.} Note that when $\beta = \frac{1}{2}$, the two strategies cross and R\&D cooperation and R\&D competition prescribe the same level of R\&D expenditure. We denote R\&D expenditure at this level as $\Bar{x}$.

To compare different equilibria on social welfare, we adopt the following utilitarian social welfare function. 

\begin{definition}
\label{welfareFunction}
The \textbf{utilitarian welfare function} is given by the sum of consumer and producer surplus. In a symmetric equilibrium where $x = x_i = x_j$, it can be expressed as
\begin{equation}
\label{welfareFunction1}
W(Q) = aQ - \frac{1}{2}bQ^2 - \alpha Q + (1+\beta)xQ - \gamma x^2
\end{equation}
where $aQ - \frac{1}{2}bQ^2$ represents the sum of consumer and producer surplus\\
$(\alpha - (1+\beta)x)Q$ represents total production costs\\
$\gamma x^2$ represents total R\&D costs
\end{definition}


\begin{proposition}
\label{socialWelfareResult}
Under assumptions \ref{basicAssumption} and \ref{concavityAssumption}, the social welfare under R\&D cooperation, $W(Q(\hat{x}))$, is inefficient but higher than the social welfare under R\&D competition, $W(Q(x^*))$, when spillover is high, $\beta > \frac{1}{2}$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}

Since we are considering between two cases where Cournot competition occurs in the second stage, we know that $q_i$ can always be expressed as a function of $x_i$ and $x_j$.

\begin{equation}
\label{quantityEquation}
q_i^* = \frac{a-\alpha+(2-\beta)x_i+(2\beta-1)x_j}{3b}    
\end{equation}

Symmetry further gives us $x_1 = x_2 = x$ and $q_1 = q_2 = \frac{Q}{2}$. Therefore, we can express the welfare function in equation \ref{welfareFunction1} in terms of $x$\footnote{With slight abuse of notation, we use $W(x)$ to represent $W(Q(x))$}.
\begin{align}
\label{welfareFunction2}
    W(Q) &= aQ - \frac{1}{2}bQ^2 - \alpha Q + (1+\beta)xQ - \gamma x^2\\
    W(x) &= \frac{4\beta^2x^2+8\beta x^2-9bx^2\gamma+4x^2+8ax-8\alpha x+8a\beta x-8\alpha \beta x+4a^2+4\alpha^2-8a\alpha}{9b}\\
    &= \frac{(4\beta^2+8\beta-9b\gamma+4)x^2+(8a-8\alpha+8a\beta-8\alpha \beta)x+(4a^2+4\alpha^2-8a\alpha)}{9b}
\end{align}

The first order condition gives the efficient level of individual R\&D with Cournot competition in the second stage.
\begin{align}
\label{optimalx}
    x^{o} = \frac{(a-\alpha)(1+\beta)}{\frac{9}{4}b\gamma-(1+\beta)^2}
\end{align}

Under assumption \ref{concavityAssumption}, the efficient level of R\&D expenditure is greater than R\&D expenditure under R\&D competition or R\&D cooperation for any $\beta \in [0,1]$. 
\begin{align*}
    x^{o} - x^* &= \frac{6.75\beta b \gamma(a-\alpha)}{(\frac{9}{4}b\gamma-(1+\beta)^2)(4.5b\gamma-(2-\beta)(1+\beta))} > 0\\
    x^{o} - \hat{x} &= \frac{2.25 b\gamma (a-\alpha)(\beta+1)}{(4.5b\gamma-(1+\beta)^2)(\frac{9}{4}b\gamma-(1+\beta)^2)} > 0
\end{align*}

The second order condition, $9b\gamma > 4(1+\beta)^2$, is satisfied under assumption \ref{concavityAssumption}, so $W(x)$ is strictly concave in $x$. Since we have $\hat{x} > x^*$ when $\beta > \frac{1}{2}$ from proposition \ref{ajProposition}, we must have $W(x^*) < W(\hat{x}) < W(x^{o})$ when $\beta > \frac{1}{2}$.
\end{proof}

\begin{corollary}

Under small spillovers, $\beta < \frac{1}{2}$, $W(\hat{x}) < W(x^*) < W(x^{o})$.

\end{corollary}

\begin{figure}
\centering
\caption{Profit and welfare as functions of the spillover parameter. $a = 10, b = 1, \alpha = 8, \gamma = 2.$}
