\label{2Graphs}
\end{figure}

Proposition \ref{socialWelfareResult} can be represented by figure \ref{fig:sub2} while figure \ref{fig:sub1} shows that individual profit is always higher under R\&D cooperation than R\&D competition. The latter observation follows naturally from the fact that total profit is maximised under R\&D cooperation. Together, figure \ref{2Graphs} shows that for large spillovers, $\beta > \frac{1}{2}$, R\&D cooperation is better for both the firm and society. For small spillovers, $\beta < \frac{1}{2}$, however, R\&D cooperation is superior for profit maximisation but achieves lower social welfare than R\&D competition. This is because in the case of low spillovers, the model behaves more like a traditional Cournot model, where cooperation induces firms to reduce production (through lower R\&D investment in this model) and increase prices, thereby lowering social welfare. Therefore, when there is no uncertainty in the spillover parameter, the policy implication of this finding is simple: R\&D cooperation should be encouraged when spillover is large and discouraged when spillover is small. 

Before we introduce uncertainty into the spillover parameter, a final observation to make is that R\&D cooperation does not lead to a subgame perfect Nash equilibrium. Although R\&D cooperation increases profits for both firms, it cannot be sustained without an external binding agreement. This is because both firms' R\&D expenditure in the first stage under R\&D cooperation are not mutual best responses. Depending on the magnitude of the spillover parameter, a firm may either over or under-invest relative to the R\&D cooperation level to profit maximise. This is important when we consider repeated games in chapter 5. 

\begin{proposition}
\label{incentiveToCheat}
Under assumptions \ref{basicAssumption} and \ref{concavityAssumption}, for large spillovers, $\beta > 0.5$, a firm has an incentive to under-invest relative to the R\&D cooperation level if its competitor invests at the R\&D cooperation level. For $\beta < 0.5$, the firm has an incentive to over-invest. 
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}

The first order condition of equation \ref{ownProfits} gives us firm $i's$ best response function.
\begin{align}
\label{xbr}
    x_1^{BR}(x_2) = \frac{2(2-\beta)(a-\alpha+(2\beta -1)x_2)}{9b\gamma-2(2-\beta)^2} 
\end{align}

The difference between R\&D expenditure at the R\&D cooperation level and the best response to this is

\begin{align*}
\hat{x} - x_1^{BR}(\hat{x}) &= \frac{(a-\alpha)(1+\beta)}{4.5b\gamma-(1+\beta)^2} - \frac{2(2-\beta)(a-\alpha+(2\beta -1)\hat{x})}{9b\gamma-2(2-\beta)^2}\\
&=\frac{36ab\beta\gamma-36b\alpha\beta\gamma-18ab\gamma+18b\alpha\gamma}{(9b\gamma-2(1+\beta)^2)(9b\gamma - 2(2-\beta)^2)}\\
&=\frac{18b\gamma (a-\alpha)(2\beta - 1)}{(9b\gamma-2(1+\beta)^2)(9b\gamma - 2(2-\beta)^2)}
\end{align*}

Assumption \ref{basicAssumption} and \ref{concavityAssumption} insures that the difference is strictly greater than zero for $\beta > \frac{1}{2}$ and less than zero when $\beta < \frac{1}{2}$. Thus we have $x_1^{BR}(\hat{x}) < \hat{x}$ for $\beta > \frac{1}{2}$ and vice versa.
\end{proof}

When the spillover is low, the R\&D model is similar to a standard Cournot model. Thus, a firm has an incentive to deviate from the R\&D cooperation level of R\&D by increasing production (by over-investing relative to the R\&D cooperation level). When the spillover is high, a firm has an incentive to deviate by lowering its own R\&D investment to save on costs while free-riding on the investment of the other firm. 

\newpage
\section{Uncertainty in R\&D Spillovers}

Most studies that introduce uncertainty into the D'Aspermont and Jacquemin model focus on the role of uncertainty in R\&D success rather than uncertainty in spillover. For example, Marjit (1990) showed that a very low or very high probability of success in each firm's R\&D promotes R\&D cooperation. Our paper, however, abstracts from uncertainty in firms' own R\&D success and examines the effect of uncertainty in the spillover parameter on R\&D levels under the two strategies.\footnote{One could possibly introduce uncertainty in the probability of own R\&D success by allowing the parameter $\gamma$ to vary.} This is motivated by the fact that the appropriability of firm $i's$ R\&D to $j$ varies with firm j's absorptive capacity (Confessore and Mancuso, 2002), patent regulations (Spence, 1984) and imitation costs, all of which can be time variant. As such, competition authorities are ambivalent towards fostering R\&D cooperation when the distribution of $\beta$ is unknown. This is because if the degree of spillovers is overestimated, R\&D cooperation may be detrimental to social welfare as we saw in proposition \ref{socialWelfareResult}. In this section, however, we find that R\&D level under R\&D cooperation is more efficient than that under R\&D competition if $\beta$ has a symmetric distribution around mean $\frac{1}{2}$.

We start by examining R\&D outcomes for the two strategies when the spillover parameter, $\beta$, has a symmetric two point distribution around the mean $\mu = \frac{1}{2}$. Let the deviation from the mean be $\theta$ so that $\beta = \frac{1}{2} + \theta$ with probability $\frac{1}{2}$ and $\beta = \frac{1}{2} - \theta$ with probability $\frac{1}{2}$. Under this set up, assuming that firms are risk-neutral, we have the following result.

\begin{proposition}
\label{uncertainty1}
When $\beta$ has a two point symmetric distribution around mean $\frac{1}{2}$, R\&D level under R\&D cooperation is higher than R\&D level under R\&D competition but lower than the socially efficient level. 
\begin{equation}
    x^{*U} < \hat{x}^U < x^{oU}
\end{equation}

\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}

To derive R\&D expenditure under \textit{R\&D competition}, firms maximise own expected profits rather than the profit function in equation \ref{ownProfits}.
\begin{align*}
E\pi_i
&= \mathop{\mathbb{E}}_\beta \frac{1}{9b}[a-\alpha+(2-\beta)x_i+(2\beta-1)x_j]^2 - \gamma\frac{x_i^2}{2}\\
&= \frac{1}{2} \frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + (\frac{3}{2}+\theta)x_i -2x_j)^2 + \frac{1}{2} \frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + (\frac{3}{2}-\theta)x_i + 2x_j)^2 - \gamma \frac{x_i^2}{2}
\end{align*}

The first order condition of $\max_{x_i} E\pi_i$ gives\footnote{Here, the superscript BR implies that $x_i$ is firm $i$ best response against firm $j$.} 
\begin{equation}
\label{2ptUncertaintyBR}
      x_i^{BR} &= \frac{3(a-\alpha)-4\theta^2 x_j}{9b\gamma - 2(\frac{9}{4}+\theta^2)} \;\;\; i = 1, 2
\end{equation}

Solving, we obtain
\begin{align*}
x^{*U} = \frac{3(a-\alpha)}{9b\gamma-\frac{9}{2}+ 2\theta^2}
\end{align*}

To derive R\&D expenditure under \textit{R\&D cooperation}, firms solve the stochastic analog to equation \ref{jointProfits}
\begin{align*}
E\Pi &= \mathop{\mathbb{E}}_\beta[\frac{2}{9b}(a-\alpha+(1+\beta)x)^2 - \gamma x^2]\\
&= \frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + x)^2 + \frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + 2x)^2 - \gamma x^2
\end{align*}

Solving $\max_{x} E\Pi$, we obtain
\begin{align*}
x^{*U} = \frac{3(a-\alpha)}{9b\gamma-\frac{9}{2}- 2\theta^2}
\end{align*}

To derive the socially efficient R\&D expenditure, we solve the stochastic analog to equation \ref{welfareFunction2}, which gives us
\begin{align*}
x^{oU} = \frac{3(a-\alpha)}{\frac{9}{2} b\gamma-\frac{9}{2}- 2\theta^2}
\end{align*}

It is instructive to compare these levels with $\Bar{x}$, which we get from substituting $\beta = \frac{1}{2}$ into equation \ref{ajProposition}. 
\begin{align*}
\Bar{x} = \frac{3(a-\alpha)}{9 b\gamma-\frac{9}{2}}
\end{align*}

Comparing denominators, it is clear that $x^{*U} \leq \Bar{x} \leq \hat{x}^U<x^{oU}$. Equality holds when $\theta = 0$.
\end{proof}

\begin{figure}
    \centering
    \captionsetup{width=.66\linewidth}
    \label{fig:my_label}
    \begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    axis lines = left,
    xlabel = $\theta$,
    ylabel = $x^U$,
]
%Below the x^{*U} is defined
\addplot [
    domain=0:0.5, 
    samples=100, 
    color=red,
]
{6/(13.5+(2*x^2)};
\addlegendentry{$x^{*U}$}

%Here the \hat{x} is defined
\addplot [
    domain=0:0.5, 
    samples=100, 
    color=blue,
    ]
    {6/(13.5-(2*x^2)};
\addlegendentry{$\hat{x}^U$}

%Here the x^o is defined
\iffalse
\addplot [
    domain=0:0.5, 
    samples=100, 
    color=green,
    ]
    {6/(4.5-(2*x^2)};
\addlegendentry{$x^{oU}$}
\fi

\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{R\&D expenditure as a function of the spillover uncertainty. $a = 10, b = 1, \alpha = 8, \gamma = 2.$}
\end{figure}
The expression for the solution is simple despite the process of optimising under uncertainty. With uncertainty in the spillover parameter, firms select $x_i$ to maximise expected profits over the two states of the world, $\beta_H = \frac{1}{2} + \theta$ and $\beta_L = \frac{1}{2} + \theta$. Our results show that R\&D pattern under different strategies is similar to that under high spillover. Thus, it appears that with uncertainty in spillovers, the effect of the $\beta_H$ state dominates. Recall that we have discussed two effects of R\&D expenditure. The direct effect increases competitiveness by decreasing own unit cost while the indirect spillover effect decreases competitiveness by decreasing the competitor's unit costs. Even with uncertainty, firms under R\&D cooperation are keen to capture the spillover effect (since they maximise joint profits) by investing more than $\Bar{x}$. On the other hand, firms under R\&D competition are keen to avoid the spillover effect by investing less than $\Bar{x}$.

To ensure that the comparison between R\&D competition and R\&D cooperation is valid, we need to check that the equilibrium under R\&D competition is stable. This happens when the best response functions do not cross the 'wrong' way. It was shown that the R\&D competition equilibrium is unstable for small values of $\beta$ under no uncertainty. (Henriques, 1990) Instability of an equilibrium makes it difficult to be used as a benchmark for comparison because it cannot be reached by best reply dynamics. Unstable equilibria are also shown to predict poorly from experimental evidence. (Holt 1995) However, under assumption \ref{concavityAssumption}, equilibrium under R\&D competition can be shown to be stable under uncertainty. 

\begin{proposition}
\label{stabilityResult}
Under assumption \ref{concavityAssumption}, the R\&D levels under R\&D competition is stable for all $\theta \in [0,\frac{1}{2}]$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
The best response function under uncertainty is given in equation \ref{2ptUncertaintyBR}. The condition for stability is 
\begin{align*}
	\frac{\partial x_i}{\partial x_j} &> -1\\
    \frac{-4\theta^2}{9b\gamma - 2(\frac{9}{4}+\theta^2)} &> -1
\end{align*}
Which gives
\begin{align*}
\theta^2 < \frac{6b\gamma - 3}{4}
\end{align*}
The smallest value the RHS can take under assumption \ref{concavityAssumption} is $\frac{23}{12}$ while the largest value LHS can take is $\frac{1}{4}$. Therefore, the equilibrium under R\&D competition is stable.\footnote{The condition holds even if we use the weaker condition of $b\gamma > \frac{8}{9}$, which guarantees the concavity of the profit functions but not the social welfare function.}
\end{proof}

While proposition \ref{uncertainty1} is informative, the assumption of a two point distribution is sometimes too restrictive for application. However, the result of proposition \ref{uncertainty1} can be generalised to any symmetric distribution around $\frac{1}{2}$.

\begin{proposition}
\label{uncertaintyResult}
Proposition \ref{uncertainty1} holds for any symmetric distribution of $\beta$ around $\frac{1}{2}$. That is, R\&D competition under uncertainty results in lower R\&D expenditure compared to R\&D cooperation under uncertainty for any symmetric distribution of $\beta$. 
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
We show this by decomposing any symmetric distribution into the integral of two-point distributions. Let $g(\beta)$ be the probability density function of $\beta$. Let $f(\theta)$ be the probability density function of deviation, $\theta$. Since the distribution is symmetric around $\beta = \frac{1}{2}$, we have $f(\theta) = 2g(\theta+\frac{1}{2}), \theta \in [0, \frac{1}{2}]$. 

Under R\&D competition, firms solve
\begin{align*}
\max_{x_i} E\pi_i
&= \max_{x_i} \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \left[\frac{1}{2} \frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + (\frac{3}{2}+\theta)x_i -2x_j)^2 + \frac{1}{2} \frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + (\frac{3}{2}-\theta)x_i + 2x_j)^2 - \gamma \frac{x_i^2}{2}\right] f(\theta) d\theta
\end{align*}

Which gives,
\begin{align*}
x^{*U} = \frac{ \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} 3(a-\alpha) f(\theta) d\theta} {\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \left[9b\gamma-\frac{9}{2}+ 2\theta^2\right] f(\theta) d\theta}
\end{align*}

Similarly, under R\&D cooperation, firms solve
\begin{align*}
\max_{x} E\Pi &= \max_{x} \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \left[\frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + x)^2 + \frac{1}{9b} (a-\alpha + 2x)^2 - \gamma x^2\right] f(\theta) d\theta
\end{align*}
which gives,
\begin{align}
\label{uncertaintyBR}
x_i^{BR} &= \frac{\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} 3(a-\alpha) f(\theta) d\theta- x_j \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} 4\theta^2 f(\theta) d\theta}{\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \left[9b\gamma - 2(\frac{9}{4}+\theta^2)\right] f(\theta) d\theta} \;\;\; i = 1, 2 & x^{*U} = \frac{ \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} 3(a-\alpha)  f(\theta) d\theta} {\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \left[9b\gamma-\frac{9}{2}- 2\theta^2 \right]  f(\theta) d\theta}
\end{align}


Similarly, the socially efficient level is
\begin{align}
    x^{oU} = \frac{ \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} 3(a-\alpha)  f(\theta) d\theta} {\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \left[\frac{9}{2}b\gamma-\frac{9}{2}- 2\theta^2 \right]  f(\theta) d\theta}
\end{align}

Again, comparing denominators, we have $x^{*U} < \hat{x}^U < x^{oU}$
\end{proof}

\begin{corollary}
Under assumption \ref{concavityAssumption}, R\&D level under R\&D competition is stable for any symmetric distribution of $\beta$ around $\frac{1}{2}$ for all $\theta \in [0, \frac{1}{2}]$
\end{corollary}

\begin{proof}
Following the steps in proposition \ref{stabilityResult}, the corresponding stability condition when the distribution of $\theta$ follows $f(\theta)$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \theta^2 f(\theta)d\theta < \int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}} \frac{6b\gamma - 3}{4} f(\theta)d\theta
\end{equation}
Since we have $\theta^2 < \frac{6b\gamma - 3}{4}$ from proposition \ref{stabilityResult}, the above condition holds. 

\end{proof}

A key consideration for competition authorities in deciding whether to foster R\&D cooperation is the the degree of spillover. When spillover is large, R\&D cooperation is preferable to R\&D competition from a social welfare perspective. However, the degree of spillover is often unknown a priori. Here, proposition \ref{uncertaintyResult} suggests that even if the prior on $\beta$ follows a uniform distribution, R\&D cooperation leads to a higher expenditure level that is closer to the socially efficient level. 

\newpage
\section{Sustainability of R\&D Cooperation in an infinitely repeated game}

Since proposition \ref{uncertaintyResult} suggests that competition authorities may been keen to allow R\&D cooperation when the prior on $\beta$ follows a symmetric distribution such as a uniform distribution, a natural question to ask is whether firms can sustain R\&D cooperation in the first place. If they are not, the benefits of higher profits and social welfare are unable to be reaped even without opposition from competition authorities. We frame this problem in the context of an infinitely repeated game and consider two cases: 1) perfect monitoring and 2) imperfect public monitoring. We assume uncertainty in the $\beta$ takes the form of a uniform distribution. Under uniform distribution, the R\&D levels  under different strategies are
\begin{align}
    x^{*U} &= \frac{9(a-\alpha)}{27b\gamma - 13}\\
    \hat{x}^U &= \frac{9(a-\alpha)}{27b\gamma - 14} 
    \\
    x_i^{BR}(x_j) &= \frac{9(a-\alpha) - x_j}{27b\gamma - 13.75}
    \label{BRUniform}
\end{align}

The strategy space can be visualised in Figure \ref{BRgraph}. The best response function of each firm is plotted and the intersection represents $x^{*U}$. While $x^{oU}$ shows the socially efficient R\&D level, it cannot be achieved even when firms cooperate to maximise joint profits. However, cooperation can improve R\&D levels from $x^{*U}$ to $x^{oU}$, increasing social welfare in the process. 

\begin{figure}[h]

    \centering
    \captionsetup{width=.66\linewidth}
    \label{fig:my_label}
    \begin{tikzpicture}
    \node at (1.55,1.26) {\textbullet};

    \node at (1.74,1.46) {\textbullet};
    \node at (4.2,3.52) {\textbullet};
    \node[above right=10pt of {(1.55,1.1)}, outer sep=2pt,fill=white] {$\hat{x}^U$};
    \node[above right=10pt of {(4,3.1)}, outer sep=2pt,fill=white] {$x^{oU}$};
    \node[above right=10pt of {(0.24,0.24)}, outer sep=2pt,fill=white] {$x^{*U}$};
    
\begin{axis}[
    axis lines = left,
    xlabel = $x_j$,
    ylabel = $x_i$,
]
%Below the x_i is defined
\addplot [
    domain=0:1.9, 
    samples=100, 
    color=red,
]
{(18-x)/40.25};
\addlegendentry{$x_i^{BR}(x_j)$}

%Here the \hat{x} is defined
\addplot [
    domain=0.4:0.447, 
    samples=100, 
    color=blue,
    ]
    {18-40.25*x};
\addlegendentry{$x_j^{BR}(x_i)$}
  
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{R\&D expenditure as a function of the spillover uncertainty. $a = 10, b = 1, \alpha = 8, \gamma = 2.$}
    \label{BRgraph}
\end{figure}

Table \ref{matrix} shows the normal form representation of the first stage R\&D game assuming that play in the second stage follows a Cournot competition equilibrium. Here, $x^{BR}$ refers to a firm using the best response given the other player's strategy, as given in equation \ref{BRUniform}. When firms play their mutual best responses in the first stage, we obtain the Cournot-Nash payoff $(\pi^{*U},\pi^{*U})$. It is easy to see that $\pi_H>\hat{\pi}>\pi^*>\pi_L$. This gives us the standard prisoners' dilemma set up. 

\begin{table}[h]
    \centering
    \setlength{\extrarowheight}{2pt}
        \begin{tabular}{cc|c|c|}
          & \multicolumn{1}{c}{} & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Firm $2$}\\
          & \multicolumn{1}{c}{} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{$x^{BR}$}  & \multicolumn{1}{c}{$\hat{x}^{U}$} \\\cline{3-4}
          \multirow{2}*{Firm $1$}  & $x^{BR}$ & $(\pi^{*U},\pi^{*U})$ & $(\pi_H,\pi_L)$ \\\cline{3-4}
          & $\hat{x}^{U}$ & $(\pi_L,\pi_H)$ & $(\hat{\pi}^{U},\hat{\pi}^{U})$ \\\cline{3-4}
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Stage game matrix}
    \label{matrix}
\end{table}

We represent the discount rate with $\delta$. Under perfect monitoring and a uniform distribution of $\beta$, we have the following result.
\\
\begin{proposition}
\label{grimTrigger}
In a infinitely repeated game with uncertainty in $\beta$ and perfect monitoring, R\&D cooperation is sustainable through a grim trigger strategy if $\delta \geq \frac{\pi_H - \hat{\pi}^U}{\pi_H-\pi^{*U}}$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Suppose that each firm uses the following 'Grim Trigger' Strategy: Play $\hat{x}^U$ in every period unless someone plays $x^{BR}(\hat{x}^U)$, in which case play $x^{*U}$ forever.

It suffice to verify that there is no single period where $i$ can make a profitable deviation.\footnote{This is the 'one-stage deviation principle'} Suppose up to time $t$, $x^{BR}$ has never been played. Then, cooperation is sustainable if the discounted payoffs from cooperation are at least as high as that under deviation, that is: 
\begin{equation*}
\pi_H + \frac{\delta}{1 - \delta} \pi^{*U} > \frac{1}{1-\delta} \hat{\pi}^{U}
\end{equation*}

Simplifying, we have the condition $\delta \geq \frac{\pi_H - \hat{\pi}^{U}}{\pi_H-\pi^{*U}}$

Suppose that at time $t$, $x^{BR}(\hat{x}^U)$ has already been played, then neither deviate from the punishment phase because $(x^{*U}, x^{*U})$ in the first stage is a Nash equilibrium. 

\end{proof}

\begin{corollary}
In a repeated game with uncertainty and perfect monitoring, social welfare at the R\&D cooperation level, $\hat{x}^U$ is achievable through the grim trigger strategy.
\end{corollary}

\textbf{Imperfect Public Monitoring}

The above assumption of perfect monitoring is unrealistic because firms have no incentive to divulge R\&D expenditure information to each other. As realisations of $\beta$ are stochastic and unobservable, firm $i$ may observe the final cost reduction, $x_i + \beta x_j$, without being able to determine whether a high level of cost reduction derives from a high realisation of $\beta$ or more intensive research efforts by firm $j$. As a result, if the enforcement of the grim trigger mechanism relies on firms' own reporting of their R\&D expenditure, then each firm has an incentive to explain over-investment in R\&D with a high realisation of $\beta$. Thus, the lack of perfect monitoring foils the enforcement of the grim trigger strategy in proposition \ref{grimTrigger}.

However, because prices are observed every period, they act as a coordination device for both firms to adopt a trigger strategy.\footnote{Private observations (firm $i$'s observation of $\beta x_j$ and $j$'s observation of $\beta x_i$) cannot be used to coordinate trigger strategies because they are independent. If firm $i$ cooperates, it will assign a high probability to firm $j$ observing a good signal regardless of her own observation. Thus, the punishment phase will not be entered.} Because $x^{BR}(\hat{x}^U) < \hat{x}^U$, each firm has an incentive to under-invest in R\&D and free-ride on the R\&D efforts of the other firm. As a result, when a firm cheats and under-invests in R\&D, equilibrium quantity falls according to equation \ref{quantityEquation} and price increases. This increase in price can then be used as a gauge of whether a firm has cheated on the R\&D cooperation agreement. 

This idea of a perfect public equilibrium, in which player strategies depend on the historical public information, was suggested by Green and Porter (1984) and subsequently refined by Abreu et al (1986). The formal definition of a public strategy and a perfect public equilibrium are given below.\footnote{In our set up, public perfect equilibrium is the relevant equilibrium concept rather than subgame perfect equilibrium because the inclusion of uncertainty does not allow each player to know the action of the other player in the previous time period ($t-1)$. As a result, there is only one information set and no proper subgames and any stage.}
\begin{definition}{Public Strategy}
\label{publicStrategy}
A \textbf{public strategy} for firm $i$ is a sequence of maps $\sigma_{it}: h^t \Rightarrow A_i$,
\begin{align*}
  \text{where } &h^t \text{ is the public information at the start of period } t: h^t = (X_1, X_2, ... X_{t-1}) \\
  &A_i \text{ is the strategy set of firm $i$}
\end{align*}
\end{definition}
\begin{definition}
\label{perfectPublicEquilibrium}
A profile $(\sigma_1,\sigma_2)$ is a \textbf{perfect public equilibrium} if
\begin{align*}
  &\textbf{(1) } \sigma_i \text{ is a public strategy for all i}\\ 
  &\textbf{(2)} \text{ For each date $t$ and history $h^t$, the strategies are a Nash equilibrium from that point on.}
\end{align*}
\end{definition}

We can now identify the necessary condition for a perfect public equilibrium under partial R\&D cooperation using Porter's (1982) optimal cartel trigger price strategy. Partial cooperation in the infinitely repeated game is sustained by a finite trigger strategy where punishment is triggered for $T-1$ periods if the price rise above a threshold $\Bar{P}$. Assuming that firms revert to the R\&D competition equilibrium $(x^{*U},x^{*U})$ in the punishment phase and maintain cooperative R\&D levels $(\mu,\mu)$ in the cooperation phase, a perfect public equilibrium can be wholly characterised by $(x^*,\mu, T, \Bar{X})$. More formally, period t is the cooperation phase if
\begin{align*}
&t=0 \text{, or}\\
&t-1 \text{ is a cooperation phase and } P_t<\Bar{P}\\
&t-T \text{ is a cooperation phase and } P_{t-T}>\Bar{P}  
\end{align*}

Otherwise, period t is a punishment phase. We can now identify the necessary condition for the existence such an equilibrium. 

\begin{proposition}
The necessary condition for the tuple $(x^*,\mu, T, \Bar{X})$ to be a strongly symmetric perfect public equilibrium is 
\begin{equation}
\label{ppeCondition}
\left(1- \delta + (\delta-\delta^T)\left[\frac{a+2\alpha-3\Bar{P}}{2\mu} - 1\right]\right)\pi_1^1(\mu,\mu) + (\pi_1(\mu,\mu) - \pi^*)\left[\frac{(\delta - \delta^T)(a+2\alpha-3\Bar{P})}{4\mu^2}\right] = 0
\end{equation}
\begin{align*}
\text{where } &\pi_1^1(\mu,\mu) \text{ is the first derivative of firm 1's profit function evaluated at } \mu
\end{align*}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}

Let $\Pi_1(x_1)$ be the net present value of future payoffs if firm 1 plays $x_1$ in the cooperative phase
\begin{equation*}
\Pi_i(x_1) = \mathop{\mathbb{E}}_\beta \sum_{t=0}^\infty \delta^t \pi_i(x_1,x_2,\beta)
\end{equation*}
Assuming firm $2$ follows the equilibrium strategy, the stationary nature of the game allows us to decompose $\Pi_1(x_1)$ into today's payoff and the expected continuation payoff 
\begin{equation}
\label{decomposedEquation}
\Pi_1(x_1) = \pi_1(x_1,\mu) + \delta \Pr(P\geq \Bar{P})\Pi_1(x_1) + \Pr(P> \Bar{P})\left[\sum_{t=1}^{t-1} \delta^t \pi^*+\delta^T \Pi_1(x_1)\right]
\end{equation}

Since we have assumed $\beta$ to follow a uniform distribution, the probabilities can be expressed as
\begin{align*}
\Pr(P < \Bar{P}) &= \Pr( \frac{a+2\alpha-(1+\beta)(x_1+\mu)}{3} < \Bar{P})\\
&= Pr(\beta> \frac{a+2\alpha-3\Bar{P}}{x_1+ \mu} - 1)\\
&= 2 - \frac{a+2\alpha - 3\Bar{P}}{x_1 + \mu} \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\; 
\text{if } 2 - \frac{a+2\alpha - 3\Bar{P}}{x_1 + \mu} \in [0,1]\\
&= 1- G
\end{align*}
Rearranging and simplifying equation \ref{decomposedEquation}, we have 
\begin{align*}
\Pi_1(x_1) &= \frac{\pi_1(x_1,\mu) + G\frac{\delta - \delta^T}{1-\delta} \pi^*}{1 - \delta +(\delta - \delta^T)G}\\
&= \frac{\pi_1(x_1,\mu) -\pi^*}{1 - \delta +(\delta - \delta^T)G} + \frac{\pi^*}{1-\delta}
\end{align*}

For $(x^*,\mu, T, \Bar{X})$ to be a Nash Equilibrium, we must have 
\begin{align*}
\Pi_1(\mu) &\geq \Pi_1(x_1), \quad\text{for all } x_1
\end{align*}

The first order conditions is
\begin{align*}
\Pi_1'(\mu) = 0
\end{align*}

Which gives

\begin{equation*}
\left(1- \delta + (\delta-\delta^T)\left[\frac{a+2\alpha-3\Bar{P}}{2\mu} - 1\right]\right)\pi_1^1(\mu,\mu) + (\pi_1(\mu,\mu) - \pi^*)\left[\frac{(\delta - \delta^T)(a+2\alpha-3\Bar{P})}{4\mu^2}\right] = 0
\end{equation*}

\end{proof}

Equation \ref{decomposedEquation} shows that net present value of profits as a sum of future discounted Nash profits and a weighted value of the difference between the cooperation profits and the Nash profits. This first order condition gives, equation \ref{ppeCondition}. This states the necessary first order condition for the existence of a perfect public equilibrium using a finite period trigger strategy. For a marginal decrease in R\&D expenditure, the LHS term captures the positive effect this would have on one period deviation profits while the RHS term captures the negative effect on net present value profits due to the higher chance of Nash reversion. 

Unlike the grim trigger strategy, which only reaches a punishment phase one either firm cheats, the finite trigger strategy leads to punishment even when neither party cheats. The idea behind this is that although the punishment phase is triggered by a large negative realisation of $\beta$ and not cheating behaviour, the punishment provides the disincentive against cheating. Thus, in equilibrium, while periods of punishment phases do happen, no firm has an incentive to deviate from their cooperative equilibrium strategy. 

For $(x^*,\mu, T, \Bar{P})$ to be a Nash Equilibrium, we require further that the net present value function $\Pi_1(x_1)$ be concave in $x_1$. The follow proposition ensures this. 

\begin{proposition}
If $G(\theta)$ is concave, then $\Pi_1(x_1)$ is concave in $x_1$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
\textbf{Work in progress}
\end{proof}
\begin{proposition}
For the optimal $T, \Bar{P}$, the perfect public equilibrium level of R\&D, $\mu$, is less than the R\&D cooperative level under uncertainty, $\hat{x}^U$.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
\textbf{Work in progress}
\end{proof}

